      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted NIH within 15% of measured NIH at the validation operating point.",
      "rationale": "Predicted NIH agreed with measured NIH within 8% at the nominal validation point (150 Pa, 500 ms). The acceptance criterion of 15% is met. Note that this comparison is performed at a single operating condition; the broader COU encompasses four additional flow-speed combinations at different shear stress levels."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (hemolysis index, relative hemolysis index RH) are directly linked to the clinical endpoint and acceptance criterion RH < 1.",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) and the derived relative hemolysis index (RH = NIH_device / NIH_predicate). These quantities directly map to the regulatory acceptance criterion RH < 1 and are standard hemolysis metrics in FDA guidance. Relevance is high."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation geometry and flow conditions are sufficiently similar to the COU pump geometry and operating envelope to support extrapolation.",
      "rationale": "Validation was performed using the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry under operating conditions overlapping the COU nominal point. The G-W correlation coefficients were derived from Couette flow experiments that share the same fluid (bovine blood, hematocrit 35%) as the COU. Relevance is considered sufficient for MRL 2. The theoretical precondition that the linear damage accumulation integral applies uniformly across the COU operating envelope is assumed to hold based on the nominal-point validation, but no explicit cross-range verification was performed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residual convergence to 1e-5 for all equations; mass imbalance < 0.01%.",
      "rationale": "All production simulations converged to scaled residuals below 1e-5 for continuity, momentum, and turbulence equations. Global mass imbalance was below 0.005% in all cases. Convergence monitors for hemolysis index showed variation below 0.1% over the final 500 iterations."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup reviewed by independent analyst; boundary conditions and material properties verified against COU specification.",
      "rationale": "An independent CFD analyst reviewed the simulation setup, boundary conditions, and post-processing scripts prior to production runs. Material properties (blood viscosity, density) and inlet/outlet boundary conditions were verified against the COU specification document. No use errors were identified."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form selection (turbulence model, hemolysis correlation) is justified by literature and prior validation studies for similar pump geometries and operating conditions.",
      "rationale": "The SST k-omega turbulence model was selected based on published validation studies for centrifugal blood pumps demonstrating superior near-wall accuracy relative to k-epsilon variants. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis correlation is the standard model form for scalar damage integral approaches in FDA submissions. The G-W model is predicated on the assumption that RBC damage accumulates as a linear integral of instantaneous stress-weighted exposure — a theoretical precondition explicitly stated in the original G-W derivation (Giersiepen et al., 1990). The package confirms this assumption at the nominal operating point via the Couette viscometer validation (ValidationResult gw-correlation-single-point), where shear stress is 150 Pa. However, the COU encompasses five flow-speed combinations spanning shear stresses from approximately 80 Pa to 320 Pa, and the linearity precondition has not been independently verified across this full range for the subject pump geometry."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
